I assume by walking machine you mean something like a treadmill type
exercise machine with variable speeds?

If so my first guess is that it is switching some resonably inductive
loads to do the speed control without adequate filtering of the nasty
spikes this tends to cause. These spikes are making there way back to
your DSL modem either via the electrical power circuit, or possibly (but
less likely) via the telephone lines. If you have a mate who is
reasonably electrically competent you can usually salvage a low pass
filter from an old PC power supply and get him to make up a cable to go
between the walking machine and the wall to cut this down. However the
best option would be to get the walking machine repaired if its under
warranty.

Another option is to wind the power lead that goes to the DSL modem thru
a ferrite ring a few times and see if that helps.
http://www.maplin.co.uk/Module.aspx?ModuleNo=29788
Only problem is I dont know where you can easily lay your hands on one
in NZ. DSE is no longer any use for this type of thing.

Avoid the cheap &quot;surge protector&quot; wall wart type devices, they have a
limited life when dealing with this sort of spike.

HTH
